              line-height: 1.2;
              font-weight: 500;
              margin-top: 2px !important;">What is contango?</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.altdaily.co/email/images/an-dec-13-4.jpg" alt="What is contango?" href="https://www.altdaily.co" />
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4">Contango happens when the future price of a product, like oil or wheat, is higher than its current price (spot price). This usually occurs when people expect the price of the product to rise over time due to storage costs, inflation, or expectations of higher future demand.</p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4">
          For example, if oil is $80 per barrel today but a futures contract for delivery in six months costs $85, the market is in contango. Buyers are willing to pay extra for the convenience of locking in a future supply, while sellers charge more to cover storage and other costs.</p>
           <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4">Contango is common in stable markets where there’s no immediate shortage. However, it can be costly for traders holding futures because they need to “roll” their contracts—selling the expiring ones and buying more expensive new ones—resulting in losses over time, known as a "negative roll yield."</p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
